76561198037157856,Recommended,281920,33920674,Posted: 30 July,all,trottier.wong,"Now that I've finished the game, I feel compelled to write a review.If you like top down shooters, this is a lot of fun. You get a good variety of enemies, weapons, and scenarios. Sometimes you get to operate a car, or rescue distressed civilians, or defend settlements. If you like to just destroy stuff, this is really fun.The graphics are not ""amazing"" but they get the job done. Despite the dark ambience, you can mostly see things clearly -- except when you're clearly not supposed to. Though games like these tend to be dreary, I was pleasantly surprised by the variety of colour. The cutscene graphics, however, are cringeworthy. More on that later.One thing I love about this game is that it runs on a variety of hardware. If you have any PC made within the past 5 years, whether Windows, Mac, or Linux, you'll be able to run this game fine. Trust me, in addition to my plethora of Windows hardware, I also own a Thinkpad T440p running Ubuntu as well as a MacBook Air (2015). The game works on all of them.This game also has full controller support, but with games like these, you're far better going mouse and keyboard. Sure, you could wield double analog sticks, but the real fun is with pointing at the enemies and laying them to waste.Not all is good, however. The in game art style is great but the cut scenes are ""fedorable"". For some reason, the designers thought a shadowy man holding a fedora over his head looks cool but all I could think of was Neckbeard RPG. There's also lots of spelling and grammar problems in the subtitles, and the voice acting is over the top. If you like ""so bad it's good"" B-movies, maybe you'll like this, but I don't think it goes well with the game.Still, the cutscenes are skippable. The real meat of the game is the overhead shooting. And in that, Splatter succeeds very well.Overall rating: 3.5/5"
