,Recommended,281920,32201922,Posted: 5 June,all,hitt.william,"7/10I really enjoyed this title. I won't go into what the game is, as it's really quite straightforward and well-conveyed by the description. I didn't expect to enjoy myself as much as I did, because everything seems so low-budget. The voice acting isn't stellar, and seems to get worse as the game goes on. Some of the graphical assets look like something from the old Windows game ""Chip's Challenge."" However, the game is very stable. I only ran into one glitch in the entirety of my play-through - a worm boss got stuck on a structure in the lower right corner of the map during our fight. However, this just made the boss a little easier, it didn't require any sort of restart to the level or the game.The game makes some very smart design decisions. First of all, the weapon system is solid. Each weapon feels notably different, and changes meaningfully with each upgrade purchase. The game does a pretty wonderful job of creating tension. The music during fights is not especially noteworthy but serves its purpose. The player takes very few hits (especially on the ""Nasty"" difficulty level), and when the player is at low health, the colors (graphically) in the game become washed out. This makes it difficult to discern the environment and the enemies. This serves as an added incentive to avoid taking hits, and makes being at low health more pulse-pounding.There are a few rough difficulty spikes, and the game involved quite a bit of kiting. However, there are a few times the game spawns enemies behind you or puts you in a tight corridor with nowhere to run. Kiting doesn't work in these situations, and you'll need flares and firepower to stay upright. If you're a fan of tense, scary titles, and wouldn't be put off by a low-budget feel, I think you'll find a lot to like here."
